   JUSTICE DEPARTMENT admits it defamed former official.
   In an unusual admission of error, the Justice Department
conceded that it had mistakenly accused Roger Pilon, a former
department official, of disclosing classified information to
a foreign government and then resigning from his post in the
face of removal proceedings.
   The department made the admission, together with a formal
apology and a settlement of $25,000, in documents signed on
Thursday. But department officials didn't announce the action
publicly. Mr. Pilon, now an officer of the Cato Institute, a
Washington research group, disclosed the documents yesterday.
   In a letter to Mr. Pilon's lawyer, Assistant Attorney
General Stuart Gerson acknowledged that a report widely
distributed last November by the department's Office of
Professional Responsibility "incorrectly stated" that a
counter-intelligence investigation into allegations that Mr.
Pilon had provided the South African government with
classified documents "discovered that sufficient cause
existed to terminate (Mr. Pilon's) political appointment."
The report also mistakenly stated that Mr. Pilon resigned
from his job as director of the department's office of asylum
policy "prior to the initiation of removal proceedings."
   In fact, Mr. Gerson continued, the 1988 investigation
exonerated Mr. Pilon. After having been put on administrative
leave of absence, Mr. Pilon resumed his post and his "top
secret" security clearance was returned. Moreover, his
subsequent resignation "was not made in the face of removal
proceedings," Mr. Gerson wrote.
   A department spokesman declined to answer questions as to
whether anyone in the Office of Professional Responsibility
would be disciplined for issuing the incorrect report.
   Mr. Pilon called the incident a "Kafkaesque nightmare . .
. because we never knew where the accusations came from." His
wife, Juliana, also was investigated for allegedly disclosing
classified information, but she was never charged.
   Rep. Don Edwards (D., Calif.), one of several lawmakers
who had pressured Attorney General Dick Thornburgh to
publicly exonerate Mr. Pilon, praised the admission, but he
added, "This apology is long overdue."
